part1.converted_description:
You are given a list of IP addresses. An IP supports TLS if it contains an ABBA (a four-character sequence with a pair of two different characters followed by the reverse of that pair), but does not have an ABBA within any hypernet sequences (sequences contained by square brackets). Count the number of IPs in the list that support TLS.

Input Format:
The input is a list of IP addresses, each on a separate line.

part2.converted_description:
Given the same list of IP addresses, determine which IPs support SSL. An IP supports SSL if it has an ABA (a three-character sequence with the same character twice and a different character between them) in the supernet sequences (outside square bracketed sections), and a corresponding BAB (the same characters but in reversed positions) in the hypernet sequences. Count the number of IPs in the list that support SSL.

Input Format:
The input is a list of IP addresses, each on a separate line.
